<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Blacks and Latinos attend college in increasing numbers but are less likely to 
stay in school and graduate than whites, the American Council on Education 
reported today. 
</P>
<P>
 The ACE found that blacks, Latinos, Asian Americans and Native Americans 
gained in enrollment from 1991 to 1992, but the number of white students 
declined. 
</P>
<P>
 The report said 41% of Latino students, 32% of African American students and 
30% of Native American students earn a bachelor's degree within six years. 
Rates for Asian Americans and whites are 63% and 56%, respectively. 
